Here at Ancient City Munitions, we strive to have the best American made products at very reasonable prices. Sure you can buy cheap Chinese garbage for less money, but if you want great American made parts at great prices, we can help. We are currently opening a new shop in St Augustine with enough room for a classroom where you can come build your own rifle under the supervision of a licensed gunsmith. We developed a 16" 300 blackout barrel with a pistol length gas system that has no problem cycling any 300 blackout ammunition.

300 AAC Blackout barrels
16"-$109

Custom designs and Camos available on request.

We have everything you need for your AR rilfle, dust cover, charging handle, forward assist, custom triggers, muzzle breaks, flash hiders, full line of Magpul accessories, grips, sights, gas tubes, gas blocks, ect...

We also manufacture our own line of custom ammunition. We do not make regular target ammo for 9mm, 40, 45, or 223. That stuff is just too cheap to buy from Walmart. I do have a company I deal with that does make that ammo and we do carry it. It is a little cheaper than the stuff at Walmart and they use much better components than the big companies trying to push out the cheapest stuff they can. We make a lot of AR caliber ammunition IE 300 Blackout subsonic and supersonic starting at $14 a box for Super and $20 a box for sub, we make .50 Beowulf ammunition, .458 SOCOM ammunition, and .380, 9mm, 40, 45, 50AE Hollow Point ammunition. title: For Sale:  COLT 1911  S/N 2030 4 DIGIT
postcontent:
Early 4-digit Colt model 1911,.45 auto, U.S. Property marked, blued finish, checkered wood grips, serial number 2030. This low serial number remains in good to very good untouched original conditions showing 70% original blue finish, Some erosion, light to very moderate scattered pitting, good markings, grips good with even wear, Markings are all visible and there is some bright finish on small parts and protected areas. The pistol shows all correct early major component parts including ,trigger, hammer, grips, etc. and shows early patent dates, early inspections , and a later two-tone lanyard bottom magazine. Action good 1911's ,very good.and Colt just shows honest use consistent with military use. These early 1911's went primarily to Texas and the border areas and were used before the First World War along the border in the Pancho Villa era., Which is a sign it has a remarkable military history It would be difficult to fine a more honest and untouched early 4-digit 1911, which has become prohibitively expensive in fine condition. The Colt barrel has markings-C,which might be a WWII . Recorded as one of a group shipped to Springfield Armory April 16th, 1912 1 Of 150 in shipment.


Note Colt Letter 


I have recently found the following refer. this Colt 1911 S/N 2030 ; 1-According to Clawson book the slide is wrong 2-some question refer. the Magazine, [ however it is a saw-cut which alone is worth about $500.00 ] 3-WWII barrel [ has a ââCââ marking or G ] That being said you must remember this Colt is over a 100 years old .

title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 Display Training Model [Huge
postcontent: OLT 1911 DISPLAY TRAINING MODEL Description: Measuring 32 inches tall, 50 inches long and 8 inches wide, this is a large scale model of a Colt Model 1911A1 Semi-Automatic Pistol. The slide is mobile, with the hammer spring loaded to move out of the way, a mobile slide catch and a function magazine catch, which when depressed releases a scale model magazine. A length of pipe extends down from the trigger guard, with two reinforcing sections on the front strap for mounting the display on the included floor stand. Also included is a black painted hardwood transport case. This was made by a unknown Company in 1944-1946. There were six [6] total producted, this is the only one know in existance. title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 [ made 1913 ]
postcontent:
As did every other combatant nation at the onset of the First World War, Britain suffered from arms shortages and began placing orders with American companies to help take up the slack. In 1912, the British started purchasing some 1911 pistols from Colt. With the outbreak of hostilities, it was decided to purchase additional pistols and by 1919 in excess of 17,000 had been delivered. Pistols in both .45 ACP and .455 Auto Mark I were obtained. The former were marked with a "C" serial number prefix while the latter had a "W" prefix. This 1911 serial # C-4649 caliber 45 acp was made is 1913 and a letter from the Colt archives states it was one of 20 pistols shipped to the London Armory Company on May 4, 1914. This was prior to the opening shots of the War which occurred on July 28, 1914. This pistol undoubtedly saw service in the hands of a British Officer during the Great War! The frame and slide have the British proofs. The over all finish is about 30% with the trigger, hammer, slide release and safety showing about 50% of the nitre blue finish. Barrel is marked HS on the lug and the letter P. Rifling is excellent! Grips are in good shape for a 101 year old War veteran. The magazine is a two tone correct punch and saw cut with lanyard loop. With the approaching anniversary of the start of the Great War July 28,1914 - November 11, 1918 this is your opportunity to own a piece of history. While it has not been researched yet it may be possible to discover which British Officer carried this pistol adding to the collectible and increasing the value! The Colt letter verifying the shipment information is included
June 28,2014 is the 100 year Anniversary the start of WWI.Sure this fine Colt was involved.
